habitat_description:
Northwest:
An arboreal vole endemic to the coniferous forests of northwestern California from north of San Francisco to the Klamath Mountains, Arborimus pomo occurs primarily in fog belt forests dominated by Douglas-fir, western hemlock, western red cedar, Sitka spruce, grand fir, and redwood (Adams and Hayes 1998, Wilson and Ruff 1999, Zeiner et al. 1990). Typically they can be found at forest edges adjacent to open gulches, meadows or fields although this species probably occurs in forest interiors as well. Food consists almost entirely of young needles and bark of coniferous trees including Douglas and grand firs. Nests are constructed among the tree limbs and composed of uneaten twigs and needle refuse (Wilson and Ruff 1999).
